tan]]\n[[Category:People stripped of honorary degrees]]\n[[Category:Politicians from New York City]]\n[[Category:Presbyterians from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the United States]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Abdulaziz al Saud]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Presidential Order of Excellence]]\n[[Category:Reform Party of the United States of America politicians]]\n[[Category:Republican Party (United States) presidential nominees]]\n[[Category:Republican Party Presidents of the United States]]\n[[Category:Right-wing populism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Television producers from New York City]]\n[[Category:The Trump Organization employees]]\n[[Category:Trump family|Donald]]\n[[Category:United States Football League executives]]\n[[Category:WWE Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n", "name_user": "Neutrality", "label": "safe", "comment": "link event that may be unfamiliar to reader", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donald_Trump"}
{"title_page": "Franklin Folsom", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer}}\n'''Franklin Brewster Folsom''' ([[Boulder, Colorado|Boulder]], [[Colorado]], 21 July, 1907&nbsp;\u2014 1995)&nbsp;was an American author of popular books for youth (over 80 titles published both under his own name and various [[Pseudonym|pseudonyms]]) and a pro-Soviet political activist.\n\n== Biography ==\nHe graduated from the [[University of Colorado Boulder]] in 1928. He was also a [[Rhodes Scholarship|Rhodes scholar]] at Oxford. On graduation, he dedicated himself to a career as a professional writer, and began publishing books on history and archaeology (part of which were co-authored by his wife, Mary Elting Folsom). He also worked as a guide in the [[Rocky Mountains]].\n\nHis interest for the rights of minorities (Native and Black Americans) resulted in his extensive involvement in radical leftist organizations in the US. He was one of the founding members of the [[League of American Writers]], and in 1937\u20141943&nbsp;he was its executive secretary, following the resignation of [[Waldo Frank]], who expressed doubts about Stalin's [[Moscow Trials|show trials]] in [[Moscow]]. The League closely cooperated with the [[Communist Party USA|Communist Party]], and Folsom himself was an active party member.\n\nDuring the [[McCarthyism]] campaign he published his books under various pseudonyms: Benjamin Brewster, Chase Elwell, Michael Gorham, Lyman Hopkins, Horatio D. Jones, Troy Nesbit, Philip Stander.\n\nHis wife Mary Elting (1906\u20142005)&nbsp;was a writer and a journalist (Forum Magazine). The family had a son Michael (1938-1990) and a daughter Rachel (1944).\n\n== Selected works ==\n\n=== Published under his own name ===\n\n* ''Search In The Desert'' (1955) \n* ''Fury and The Mystery At Trappers' Hole'' (1959) \n*  ''Wagon Train'' (1959) \n* ''The Story of Archaeology of The Americas'' (1960) by Franklin Folsom and Mary Elting Folsom\n* ''America's Ancient Treasures: A Guide To Archaeological Sites and Museums In The United States and Canada'' (1962) by Franklin Folsom and Mary Elting Folsom\n* ''Famous Pioneers'' (1963) \n* ''The Language Book: From Tom Toms To Telstar'' (1963), illustrated by John Hull & Tran Hawicke\n** Russian translation: ''\u041a\u043d\u0438\u0433\u0430 \u043e \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0435'' (1974) \u041c. \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0441\n** French translation: ''Du tam-tam \u00e0 telstar, l'aventure du langage''\n** Extended version: ''The whole dramatic story of language: What it is . . . How it began . . . How it changes'' (1963)\n* ''Soviet Union : The View from Within'' (1965)\n* ''Science and The Secret of Man's Past'' (1966)\n* ''The Answer Book of History'' (1966) by Mary Elting Folsom & Franklin Folsom\n* ''Flags of All Nations and The People Who Live Under Them'' (1967) by Mary Elting Folsom & Franklin Folsom\n* ''If You Lived In The Days of The Wild Mammoth Hunters'' (1968) by Franklin Folsom and his wife Mary Elting Folsom\n* ''The Life and Legend of George McJunkin: Black Cowboy'' (ages 10 & up; 1973)\n* ''Red Power On The Rio Grande: The Native American Revolution of 1680'' (1973)\n* ''Indian Uprising On The Rio Grande: The Pueblo Revolt of 1680'' (1996)\n* ''Impatient Armies of The Poor: The Story of Collective Action of The Unemployed, 1808\u20141942'' (1991)\n* ''Days of Anger, Days of Hope: A Memoir of The League of American Writers, 1937\u20141942'' (1994)\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://snaccooperative.org/ark:/99166/w6dw4m1x Mary Elting, Franklin Folsom, and Michael Folsom]\n* [https://www.genordell.com/stores/spirit/FranklinFolsom.htm Short biography of F. Folsom]\n* [https://best.berkeley.edu/george-allen-agogino/memoir-in-honor-of-franklin-folsom/ Memoir in honor of Franklin Folsom]\n\n[[Category:Members of the Communist Party USA]]\n[[Category:American children's writers]]\n[[Category:1995 deaths]]\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:University of Colorado alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:American Rhodes Scholars]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer}}\n'''Franklin Brewster Folsom''' ([[Boulder, Colorado|Boulder]], [[Colorado]], 21 July, 1907&nbsp;\u2014 1995)&nbsp;was an American author of popular books for youth (over 80 titles published both under his own name and various pseudonyms) and a pro-Soviet political activist.\n\n== Biography ==\nHe graduated from the [[University of Colorado Boulder]] in 1928. He was also a [[Rhodes Scholarship|Rhodes scholar]] at Oxford. On graduation, he dedicated himself to a career as a professional writer, and began publishing books on history and archaeology (part of which were co-authored by his wife, Mary Elting Folsom). He also worked as a guide in the [[Rocky Mountains]].\n\nHis interest for the rights of minorities (Native and Black Americans) resulted in his extensive involvement in radical leftist organizations in the US. He was one of the founding members of the [[League of American Writers]], and in 1937\u20141943&nbsp;he was its executive secretary, following the resignation of [[Waldo Frank]], who expressed doubts about Stalin's [[Moscow Trials|show trials]] in [[Moscow]]. The League closely cooperated with the [[Communist Party USA|Communist Party]], and Folsom himself was an active party member.\n\nDuring the [[McCarthyism]] campaign he published his books under various pseudonyms: Benjamin Brewster, Chase Elwell, Michael Gorham, Lyman Hopkins, Horatio D. Jones, Troy Nesbit, Philip Stander.\n\nHis wife Mary Elting (1906\u20142005)&nbsp;was a writer and a journalist (Forum Magazine). The family had a son Michael (1938-1990) and a daughter Rachel (1944).\n\n== Selected works ==\n\n=== Published under his own name ===\n\n* ''Search In The Desert'' (1955) \n* ''Fury and The Mystery At Trappers' Hole'' (1959) \n*  ''Wagon Train'' (1959) \n* ''The Story of Archaeology of The Americas'' (1960) by Franklin Folsom and Mary Elting Folsom\n* ''America's Ancient Treasures: A Guide To Archaeological Sites and Museums In The United States and Canada'' (1962) by Franklin Folsom and Mary Elting Folsom\n* ''Famous Pioneers'' (1963) \n* ''The Language Book: From Tom Toms To Telstar'' (1963), illustrated by John Hull & Tran Hawicke\n** Russian translation: ''\u041a\u043d\u0438\u0433\u0430 \u043e \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0435'' (1974) \u041c. \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0441\n** French translation: ''Du tam-tam \u00e0 telstar, l'aventure du langage''\n** Extended version: ''The whole dramatic story of language: What it is . . . How it began . . . How it changes'' (1963)\n* ''Soviet Union : The View from Within'' (1965)\n* ''Science and The Secret of Man's Past'' (1966)\n* ''The Answer Book of History'' (1966) by Mary Elting Folsom & Franklin Folsom\n* ''Flags of All Nations and The People Who Live Under Them'' (1967) by Mary Elting Folsom & Franklin Folsom\n* ''If You Lived In The Days of The Wild Mammoth Hunters'' (1968) by Franklin Folsom and his wife Mary Elting Folsom\n* ''The Life and Legend of George McJunkin: Black Cowboy'' (ages 10 & up; 1973)\n* ''Red Power On The Rio Grande: The Native American Revolution of 1680'' (1973)\n* ''Indian Uprising On The Rio Grande: The Pueblo Revolt of 1680'' (1996)\n* ''Impatient Armies of The Poor: The Story of Collective Action of The Unemployed, 1808\u20141942'' (1991)\n* ''Days of Anger, Days of Hope: A Memoir of The League of American Writers, 1937\u20141942'' (1994)\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://snaccooperative.org/ark:/99166/w6dw4m1x Mary Elting, Franklin Folsom, and Michael Folsom]\n* [https://www.genordell.com/stores/spirit/FranklinFolsom.htm Short biography of F. Folsom]\n* [https://best.berkeley.edu/george-allen-agogino/memoir-in-honor-of-franklin-folsom/ Memoir in honor of Franklin Folsom]\n\n[[Category:Members of the Communist Party USA]]\n[[Category:American children's writers]]\n[[Category:1995 deaths]]\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:University of Colorado alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:American Rhodes Scholars]]\n", "name_user": "Rahammz", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Franklin_Folsom"}
{"title_page": "Germana Viana", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| name               = Germana Viana\n| image              = Germana_Viana.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Germana Viana at 2017 [[Comic Con Experience]]\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1972|10|16}}\n| birth_place        = [[Recife]], [[Pernambuco]], [[Brasil]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Universidade Estadual Paulista]]\n| occupation         =comic book artist,comic book writer, illustrator\n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Germana Viana''' (born October 16, 1972 <ref name=\"BAMQ\">{{Cite web|url=http://ladyscomics.com.br/bamq/perfil?pdb=55|title=BAMQ! \u2013 Perfil|publisher=Ladys Comics|access-date=August 9, 2019}}</ref>) is a Brazilian comic book artist and writer.\n\nBorn in [[Recife]], in 1972, Germana graduated in Arts from the [[S\u00e3o Paulo State University]] and began her career in the 1990s doing illustration for children's books.\u00a0 Since the early 2000s,she started acting as a graphic designer and comics letterer, having been assistant to [[Joe Prado]] in agencing  Brazilian artists for the North American market.<ref name=\"BAMQ\" />\n\nFrom 2013 she started publishing her own comic books, starting with the ''Lizzie Bordello e as Piratas do Espa\u00e7o'' (Lizzie Bordello and the Space Pirates) series, which was released in two volumes, respectively in 2014 and 2016, by the Jamb\u00f4 publishing house.\n\nAs of March 8, 2016, she started publishing the webcomic ''As Empoderadas'', which won the 29th HQ Mix Trophy in the \"best web comic\" category.\".<ref name=\"Nanquim\">{{Cite web|url=http://pipocaenanquim.com.br/quadrinhos-2/lizzie-bordello-e-as-piratas-do-espaco-lancamento/|title=Lizzie Bordello e as Piratas do Espa\u00e7o|date=November 19, 2014|publisher=Pipoca & Nanquim}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://impulsohq.com/quadrinhos/entrevistas/entrevista-germana-viana-lizzie-bordello-e-as-piratas-do-espaco/|title=Entrevista: Germana Viana \u2013 Lizzie Bordello e as Piratas do Espa\u00e7o|date=January 15, 2015|publisher=Impulso HQ}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://judao.com.br/sobre-germana-lizzie-e-um-bando-de-piratas-espaciais-fodonas/|title=Germana Viana e suas piratas espaciais fodonas|date= May 29, 2015|publisher=Jud\u00e3o}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.universohq.com/noticias/germana-viana-thiago-souto-marcatti-e-andre-pijamar-na-loja-ugra/|title=Germana Viana, Thiago Souto, Marcatti e Andr\u00e9 Pijamar na loja Ugra|date=April 28, 2016|publisher=[[Universo HQ]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://revistaogrito.com/papodequadrinho/2016/05/11/lizzie-bordello-de-germana-viana-ganha-nova-edicao-impressa/|title=\"Lizzie Bordello\", de Germana Viana, ganha nova edi\u00e7\u00e3o impressa|date=May 11, 2016|publisher=Revista O Grito}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.universohq.com/noticias/divulgados-os-vencedores-do-29-trofeu-hq-mix/|title=Divulgados os vencedores do 29\u00b0 Trof\u00e9u HQ Mix|date=September 1, 2017|publisher=[[Universo HQ]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.correiobraziliense.com.br/app/noticia/diversao-e-arte/2017/09/20/interna_diversao_arte,627269/hqs-deep-e-as-empoderadas.shtml|title=HQs 'D.E.E.P' e 'As empoderadas' d\u00e3o destaque a sexualidade e feminismo|date= September 20, 2017|publisher=[[Correio Braziliense]]}}</ref> She is married to writer and editor Rog\u00e9rio Saladino.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Viana, Germana}}\n[[Category:Brazilian translators]]\n[[Category:Comics artists]]\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Recife]]\n[[Category:S\u00e3o Paulo State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Brazilian female comics artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| name               = Germana Viana\n| image              = Germana_Viana.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Germana Viana at 2017 [[Comic Con Experience]]\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1972|10|16}}\n| birth_place        = [[Recife]], [[Pernambuco]], [[Brasil]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Universidade Estadual Paulista]]\n| occupation         =comic book artist,comic book writer, illustrator\n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Germana Viana''' (born October 16, 1972 <ref name=\"BAMQ\">{{Cite web|url=http://ladyscomics.com.br/bamq/perfil?pdb=55|title=BAMQ! \u2013 Perfil|publisher=Ladys Comics|access-date=August 9, 2019}}</ref>) is a Brazilian comic book artist and writer.\n\nBorn in [[Recife]], in 1972, Germana graduated in Arts from the [[S\u00e3o Paulo State University]] and began her career in the 1990s doing illustration for children's books.\u00a0 Since the early 2000s,she started acting as a graphic designer and comics letterer, having been assistant to [[Joe Prado]] in agencing  Brazilian artists for the North American market.<ref name=\"BAMQ\" />\n\nFrom 2013 she started publishing her own comic books, starting with the ''Lizzie Bordello e as Piratas do Espa\u00e7o'' (Lizzie Bordello and the Space Pirates) series, which was released in two volumes, respectively in 2014 and 2016, by the Jamb\u00f4 publishing house.\n\nAs of March 8, 2016, she started publishing the webcomic ''As Empoderadas'', which won the 29th HQ Mix Trophy in the \"best web comic\" category.\".<ref name=\"Nanquim\">{{Cite web|url=http://pipocaenanquim.com.br/quadrinhos-2/lizzie-bordello-e-as-piratas-do-espaco-lancamento/|title=Lizzie Bordello e as Piratas do Espa\u00e7o|date=November 19, 2014|publisher=Pipoca & Nanquim}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://impulsohq.com/quadrinhos/entrevistas/entrevista-germana-viana-lizzie-bordello-e-as-piratas-do-espaco/|title=Entrevista: Germana Viana \u2013 Lizzie Bordello e as Piratas do Espa\u00e7o|date=January 15, 2015|publisher=Impulso HQ}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://judao.com.br/sobre-germana-lizzie-e-um-bando-de-piratas-espaciais-fodonas/|title=Germana Viana e suas piratas espaciais fodonas|date= May 29, 2015|publisher=Jud\u00e3o}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.universohq.com/noticias/germana-viana-thiago-souto-marcatti-e-andre-pijamar-na-loja-ugra/|title=Germana Viana, Thiago Souto, Marcatti e Andr\u00e9 Pijamar na loja Ugra|date=April 28, 2016|publisher=[[Universo HQ]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://revistaogrito.com/papodequadrinho/2016/05/11/lizzie-bordello-de-germana-viana-ganha-nova-edicao-impressa/|title=\"Lizzie Bordello\", de Germana Viana, ganha nova edi\u00e7\u00e3o impressa|date=May 11, 2016|publisher=Revista O Grito}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.universohq.com/noticias/divulgados-os-vencedores-do-29-trofeu-hq-mix/|title=Divulgados os vencedores do 29\u00b0 Trof\u00e9u HQ Mix|date=September 1, 2017|publisher=[[Universo HQ]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.correiobraziliense.com.br/app/noticia/diversao-e-arte/2017/09/20/interna_diversao_arte,627269/hqs-deep-e-as-empoderadas.shtml|title=HQs 'D.E.E.P' e 'As empoderadas' d\u00e3o destaque a sexualidade e feminismo|date= September 20, 2017|publisher=[[Correio Braziliense]]}}</ref> She is married to writer and editor Rog\u00e9rio Saladino.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Viana, Germana}}\n[[Category:Brazilian translators]]\n[[Category:Comics artists]]\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Recife]]\n[[Category:S\u00e3o Paulo State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Brazilian female comics artists]]\n", "name_user": "Lucio Luiz", "label": "safe", "comment": "links added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Germana_Viana"}
{"title_page": "Gloria Fern\u00e1ndez Fern\u00e1ndez", "text_new": "Gloria Fern\u00e1ndez Fern\u00e1ndez<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Gloria Fernandez 1945-1996|publisher=\u00c1rea de Cultura. Deputaci\u00f3n de Lugo. Comisario Roberto Gonzalez|year=2008|isbn=978-84-8192-398-8|location=Provincial Museum of Lugo|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mulleresdesileminho.blogspot.com/2010/12/gloria-fernandez-pintora-monfortina.html|title=Mulleres de Sil e Minho|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> is a Spanish painter born in Monforte de Lemos, Lugo, in 1913. She died in Madrid in 1996. [[Monforte de Lemos]] is a city in northwest Spain called [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]].  She is included in the Bibliography of Galician Painters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pintoresgallegos.com/bibliografia/gloriafernandez.html|title=Bibliography of Galician Painters|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Gloria has exhibited in the Spanish cities of [[Monforte de Lemos]], [[A Coru\u00f1a]], [[Santiago de Compostela]], [[Vigo]] and [[Madrid]]. Her work includes still lifes, flowers, portraits, and human figures. She was featured in an extensive exhibit of her works at the Provincial Museum of Lugo.  The exhibiton and her work are featured in a catalog of the exhibition that includes information about her evolution as an artist.  According to M. Hermida Balado from her book ''Lemos, a small history of a place with a long history'',<ref>{{Cite book|last=Balado|first=M. Hermida|title=LEMOS, Pequena Historia De Un Lugar Con Mucha Historia.|publisher=Artes Graficas|year=1969|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> Gloria  Fern\u00e1ndez Fern\u00e1ndez was one of the pillars of the Monforte de Lemos intellectual community in the 1960s and was one of the three notable painters of the province at that time.\n\n==== individual exhibitions ====\n\n* Provincial Museum of Lugo, Lyceum of Ourense, Photo Club de Vigo (1963)\n\n* Association of Artists of A Coru\u00f1a (1964)\n\n* [[Hostal dos Reis Cat\u00f3licos]]. Santiago de Compostela (1965)\n\n* [[Museo del Prado|Prado]] Athenaeum Salon . Madrid (1969)\n\n* CAV Salon, Municipal Savings Bank of Vigo (1972)\n\n* New Exhibition Hall of the CAV (1976)\n\n==== group exhibitions ====\n\n* XV Exhibition of Culture and Art. Circle of Arts. Lugo (1956)\n\n* XVI Exhibition of Culture and Art. Circle of Arts. Lugo (1957)\n\n* Monforte de Lemos painters (with C. Cort\u00e9s and M. Bosch). Youth Radio of Monforte. Monforte de Lemos (1958)\n\n* XVII Drawing and Painting Exhibition. Provincial Union Delegation. Lugo (1958)\n\n* XVII Culture and Art Exhibition. Circle of Arts. Lugo (1959)\n\n* 1st Painting Exhibition (with M.Bosch, Celia Cort\u00e9s and Ju\u00e1n Nuevo). Monforte Casino. Monforte de Lemos (1959)\n\n* XXXIV Autumn Salon. Retiro Palace. Madrid (1963)\n\n* Galician artists. Lugo Casino. Lugo (1965)\n\n* XXXVI Autumn Salon. Retiro Palace. Madrid (1965)\n\n* Current Lugo painting. Sala da Caixa de Aforros de A Coru\u00f1a e Lugo. Lugo (1966)\n\n* XXXVII Madrid Autumn Salon (1966)\n\n* Spring Cultue Weeks in the Province of Lugo. Ministry of Information and Tourism. by Chantada, Monforte, Ribadeo e Viveiro (1966)\n\n* 1st Regional Art Biennial in Pontevedra (1970)\n\n* 1st National Biennial of Art of Pontevedra (1971)\n\n* IV Outdoor Art Exhibition. Vigo (1971)\n\n* Galician artists. Victoria Circle. Monforte de Lemos (1971)\n\n==== posthumous exhibitions ====\n\n* The Memory of Gloria Fern\u00e1ndez. Comercial Center of the Lemos Region, Monforte (2001)<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.lavozdegalicia.es/noticia/lemos/2001/10/02/cerca-cuarenta-alumnos-gloria-fernandez-participaran-homenaje-pintora/0003_767446.htm|title=About forty students of Gloria Fern\u00e1ndez will participate in the tribute to the painter|date=2 Oct 2001|work=La Voz de Galicia|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n* A retrospective 1945-1996, Museo Provincial de Lugo (2008)<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.lavozdegalicia.es/noticia/lemos/2008/04/10/obra-gloria-fernandez-museo-provincial/0003_6720284.htm|title=The work of Gloria Fern\u00e1ndez, in the provincial museum|date=10 April 2008|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== awards ====\n\n* 2nd Prize of the IX Provincial Exhibition of Painting Art in Lugo (1950)\n\n* 2nd Prize in Painting at the XIV Provincial Art Exhibition, Lugo (1955)\n\n* 2nd Prize Painting in the XV Provincial Art Exhibition, Lugo (1956)\n\n* 1st prize for painting at the XVI Provincial Art Exhibition (Lugo, 1957)\n\n* Extraordinary Mention of Painting, XVII Provincial Exhibition (1958)\n\n* Extraordinary mention in the XVIII Provincial Art Exhibition, Lugo (1959)\n\n* Special mention for her work at the XIX Provincial Art Exhibition (Lugo, 1960)\n\n* 3rd medal at the Madrid Autumn Salon (1963)\n\n<br />\n<references />\n", "text_old": "Gloria Fern\u00e1ndez Fern\u00e1ndez<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Gloria Fernandez 1945-1996|publisher=\u00c1rea de Cultura. Deputaci\u00f3n de Lugo. Comisario Roberto Gonzalez|year=2008|isbn=978-84-8192-398-8|location=Provincial Museum of Lugo|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mulleresdesileminho.blogspot.com/2010/12/gloria-fernandez-pintora-monfortina.html|title=Mulleres de Sil e Minho|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> was a Spanish painter born in Monforte de Lemos, Lugo, in 1913. She died in Madrid in 1996. [[Monforte de Lemos]] is a city in northwest Spain called [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]].  She is included in the Bibliography of Galician Painters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pintoresgallegos.com/bibliografia/gloriafernandez.html|title=Bibliography of Galician Painters|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Gloria has exhibited in the Spanish cities of Monforte de Lemos, [[A Coru\u00f1a]], [[Santiago de Compostela]], [[Vigo]] and [[Madrid]]. Her work includes still lifes, flowers, portraits, and human figures. She was featured in an extensive exhibit of her works at the Provincial Museum of Lugo.  The exhibiton and her work are featured in a catalog of the exhibition that includes information about her evolution as an artist. According to M. Hermida Balado from her book ''Lemos, a small history of a place with a long history'',<ref>{{Cite book|last=Balado|first=M. Hermida|title=LEMOS, Pequena Historia De Un Lugar Con Mucha Historia.|publisher=Artes Graficas|year=1969|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> Gloria  Fern\u00e1ndez Fern\u00e1ndez was one of the pillars of the Monforte de Lemos intellectual community in the 1960s and was one of the three notable painters of the province at that time.\n\n==== individual exhibitions ====\n\n* Provincial Museum of Lugo, Lyceum of Ourense, Photo Club de Vigo (1963)\n\n* Association of Artists of A Coru\u00f1a (1964)\n\n* [[Hostal dos Reis Cat\u00f3licos]]. Santiago de Compostela (1965)\n\n* [[Museo del Prado|Prado]] Athenaeum Salon . Madrid (1969)\n\n* CAV Salon, Municipal Savings Bank of Vigo (1972)\n\n* New Exhibition Hall of the CAV (1976)\n\n==== group exhibitions ====\n\n* XV Exhibition of Culture and Art. Circle of Arts. Lugo (1956)\n\n* XVI Exhibition of Culture and Art. Circle of Arts. Lugo (1957)\n\n* Monforte de Lemos painters (with C. Cort\u00e9s and M. Bosch). Youth Radio of Monforte. Monforte de Lemos (1958)\n\n* XVII Drawing and Painting Exhibition. Provincial Union Delegation. Lugo (1958)\n\n* XVII Culture and Art Exhibition. Circle of Arts. Lugo (1959)\n\n* 1st Painting Exhibition (with M.Bosch, Celia Cort\u00e9s and Ju\u00e1n Nuevo). Monforte Casino. Monforte de Lemos (1959)\n\n* XXXIV Autumn Salon. Retiro Palace. Madrid (1963)\n\n* Galician artists. Lugo Casino. Lugo (1965)\n\n* XXXVI Autumn Salon. Retiro Palace. Madrid (1965)\n\n* Current Lugo painting. Sala da Caixa de Aforros de A Coru\u00f1a e Lugo. Lugo (1966)\n\n* XXXVII Madrid Autumn Salon (1966)\n\n* Spring Cultue Weeks in the Province of Lugo. Ministry of Information and Tourism. by Chantada, Monforte, Ribadeo e Viveiro (1966)\n\n* 1st Regional Art Biennial in Pontevedra (1970)\n\n* 1st National Biennial of Art of Pontevedra (1971)\n\n* IV Outdoor Art Exhibition. Vigo (1971)\n\n* Galician artists. Victoria Circle. Monforte de Lemos (1971)\n\n==== posthumous exhibitions ====\n\n* The Memory of Gloria Fern\u00e1ndez. Comercial Center of the Lemos Region, Monforte (2001)<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.lavozdegalicia.es/noticia/lemos/2001/10/02/cerca-cuarenta-alumnos-gloria-fernandez-participaran-homenaje-pintora/0003_767446.htm|title=About forty students of Gloria Fern\u00e1ndez will participate in the tribute to the painter|date=2 Oct 2001|work=La Voz de Galicia|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n* A retrospective 1945-1996, Museo Provincial de Lugo (2008)<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.lavozdegalicia.es/noticia/lemos/2008/04/10/obra-gloria-fernandez-museo-provincial/0003_6720284.htm|title=The work of Gloria Fern\u00e1ndez, in the provincial museum|date=10 April 2008|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== awards ====\n\n* 2nd Prize of the IX Provincial Exhibition of Painting Art in Lugo (1950)\n\n* 2nd Prize in Painting at the XIV Provincial Art Exhibition, Lugo (1955)\n\n* 2nd Prize Painting in the XV Provincial Art Exhibition, Lugo (1956)\n\n* 1st prize for painting at the XVI Provincial Art Exhibition (Lugo, 1957)\n\n* Extraordinary Mention of Painting, XVII Provincial Exhibition (1958)\n\n* Extraordinary mention in the XVIII Provincial Art Exhibition, Lugo (1959)\n\n* Special mention for her work at the XIX Provincial Art Exhibition (Lugo, 1960)\n\n* 3rd medal at the Madrid Autumn Salon (1963)\n\n<br />\n<references />\n", "name_user": "Jvas41", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gloria_Fern%C3%A1ndez_F